Tulane University president elected to American Academy of Arts and Sciences






Print
Email


John Pope, NOLA.com | The Times-Picayune

	



	



By

	
		
	
		
			
	
		
	
	
	
	
	John Pope, NOLA.com | The Times-Picayune

The Times-Picayune
 Email the author | Follow on Twitter
on April 19, 2010 at  9:15 PM, updated April 19, 2010 at  9:25 PM









 comments

















Tulane University President Scott Cowen is one of 229 leaders in science, public affairs and the arts and humanities who have been elected members of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, a 230-year-old center for independent policy research.
Tulane University President Scott Cowen 

The academy, which issued the list of inductees Monday, was founded by a group that included John Adams and John Hancock. Among its members have been George Washington, Benjamin Franklin, Daniel Webster, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Albert Einstein and Winston Churchill. Membership is for life. 

"To think that I'm amongst the giants who have been in there humbles me," Cowen, 63, said Monday. "I am just very surprised and very pleased. This is one of the most prestigious honors you can receive."

Others elected with Cowen include actors Denzel Washington and John Lithgow; director Francis Ford Coppola; jazz saxophonist Sonny Rollins; dancer Suzanne Farrell; G. Wayne Clough, secretary of the Smithsonian Institution; Stephen Bosworth, United States' special envoy to North Korea; David Ferriero, archivist of the United States; and James Leach, chairman of the National Endowment for the Humanities.

The induction ceremony will be held Oct. 9 at the academy's headquarters in Cambridge, Mass.

The academy studies complex and emerging policies in such fields as science, technology, global security, social policy, the humanities, culture and education.

Members are called upon to work on these projects. Cowen, who learned of his election Friday night, said he does not know yet what his work will include.

This is the latest in a series of honors for Cowen, who has been Tulane's president since July 1998. This year's recipient of The Times-Picayune Loving Cup, Cowen has received the Carnegie Corporation Academic Leadership Award and been named one of the nation's top 10 college presidents by Time magazine.

He has been a leader in the Hurricane Katrina recovery effort. Mayor Ray Nagin appointed him to the Bring New Orleans Back Commission and the New Orleans Redevelopment Authority, and Cowen founded the Fleur de Lis Ambassadors to barnstorm the country to ensure that Americans remember and care about New Orleans.

As a result of his education-related work on the Bring New Orleans Back Commission, Cowen founded the Cowen Institute for Public Education Initiatives.

John Pope can be reached at jpope@timespicayune.com or 504.826.3317.




































